    <tr>
        <td><b>Title</b></td>
        <td><span id="ctl00_cph_infoSubmission_lblPaperTitle" style="font-size:Small;">Fisher vector places: learning compact image descriptors for place recognition</span></td>
    </tr>
    
    
    
    
    
</tbody></table></span>
    
    
            <hr />
            <table>
                <tbody><tr>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl00_Label2" style="font-size:Small;font-weight:bold;">Masked Reviewer ID:</span>
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl00_Label1" style="font-size:Small;">Assigned_Reviewer_18</span>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl00_Label3" style="font-size:Small;font-weight:bold;">Review:</span>
                    </td>
                    <td>
                    </td>
                </tr>
            </tbody></table>
            <div>
		<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" rules="all" border="1" style="color:#333333;border-width:1px;border-style:None;font-family:Verdana;font-size:Small;border-collapse:collapse;">
			<tbody><tr style="color:White;background-color:#5D7B9D;font-weight:bold;">
				<th scope="col">Question</th><th scope="col">&nbsp;</th>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Comments to author(s).  First provide a summary of the paper, and then address the following criteria:  Quality, clarity, originality and significance.   (For detailed reviewing guidelines, see http://nips.cc/PaperInformation/ReviewerInstructions)</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            This paper presents an approach for place recognition. Fisher vector coding of densely extracted SIFT features is used as the feature representation of each image. As was done by Gronat et al., a per-exemplar SVM is trained for each image, where the image is the only positive example and images from other places as negative examples. <br /><br />In Gronat et al. a calibration procedure is performed to make classifier scores comparable. Given a query image, Gronat et al. evaluates every per-exemplar classifier and the query image is assigned the location of the image with the highest score. This paper argues instead that no score calibration is required. Given a query image, the dot product between each L2-normalized exemplar classifier hyperplane and the fisher vector of the query image is computed and the query image is assigned the location of the database image where this dot product is maximum. <br /><br />It is not clear from the analysis in the paper why one can use the L2-normalized weight vector as the new feature representation. This conclusion runs counter to the claim of Gronat et al. that exemplar SVM scores cannot be compared directly. The analysis in this paper is not unique to the use of fisher vectors or to the use of exemplar SVMs, so perhaps the authors should clarify why the proposed approach does not require calibration, while the method of Gronat et al. and the original exemplar SVM work of Malisiewicz et al. do. Regardless, a key limitation of using the L2-normalized weight directly is that one cannot reject query images as being from a location not in the database, as the threshold for doing so would be different for each database image. The authors should explicitly mention this limitation in the paper.<br /><br />Experiments on place recognition demonstrate that the resulting fisher vectors achieve better performance than bag-of-visual-words approaches and to using fisher vectors without remapping. While these comparisons are informative, the paper should also provide a comparison between using the L2-normalized weight vector directly and using a score calibration procedure, e.g. similar to that of Gronat et al.<br /><br />Overall, the paper presents an interesting approach for place recognition. However, the key design choice of using L2-normalized weight vectors from exemplar SVMs directly and ignoring the bias term requires more theoretical justification and empirical validation.<br /><br /><br />Typo: <br />- eq. 4: b_j should be b<br />- line 196: trivial solution should be ||w|| = 0 and b = 1<br />
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#284775;background-color:White;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Please summarize your review in 1-2 sentences</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            The paper presents an interesting approach for place recognition using exemplar SVMs trained on database images represented using fisher vectors. However, the key design choice of using L2-normalized weight vectors from exemplar SVMs directly and ignoring the bias term requires more theoretical justification and empirical validation.
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Quality Score - Does the paper deserves to be published?</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            4: An OK paper, but not good enough
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#284775;background-color:White;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Impact Score - Independently of the Quality Score above, this is your opportunity to identify papers that are very different, original, or otherwise potentially impactful for the NIPS community.</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            1: This work is incremental and unlikely to have much impact even though it may be technically correct and well executed.
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Confidence</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            4: Reviewer is confident but not absolutely certain
                        </td>
			</tr>
		</tbody></table>
	</div>
            
        
            <hr />
            <table>
                <tbody><tr>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl01_Label2" style="font-size:Small;font-weight:bold;">Masked Reviewer ID:</span>
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl01_Label1" style="font-size:Small;">Assigned_Reviewer_34</span>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl01_Label3" style="font-size:Small;font-weight:bold;">Review:</span>
                    </td>
                    <td>
                    </td>
                </tr>
            </tbody></table>
            <div>
		<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" rules="all" border="1" style="color:#333333;border-width:1px;border-style:None;font-family:Verdana;font-size:Small;border-collapse:collapse;">
			<tbody><tr style="color:White;background-color:#5D7B9D;font-weight:bold;">
				<th scope="col">Question</th><th scope="col">&nbsp;</th>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Comments to author(s).  First provide a summary of the paper, and then address the following criteria:  Quality, clarity, originality and significance.   (For detailed reviewing guidelines, see http://nips.cc/PaperInformation/ReviewerInstructions)</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            The paper presents a novel approach to large scale place recognition. The authors combine the idea of Fisher vector descriptors with the exemplar SVM approach. They show that the learned SVM weights can be used as a compact descriptor in place of the original Fisher vector. Experiments show improvements in recall when considering descriptors of the same size.<br /><br />The paper quality is very good. The basic idea is quite interesting and easy to grasp. I would have preferred a more formal analysis of the SVM objective. This could be achieved using comparative static techniques (as in economics for instance) where the implicit function theorem is used to linearly approximate the optimality conditions. I also believe that there is a mistake in Figure 4, second row. The second image retrieved by the proposed approach and the third retrieved by Fisher vector are the same image but it is marked as wrong for the Fisher vector case.<br /><br />The paper is very well written and clear. I found one sentence hard to understand though. It is at page 6, rows 313-315. I would also improve the notation by writing all vectors using boldface fonts, so to distinguish them from scalars.<br /><br />The work is a novel combination of known techniques (Fisher vectors and exemplar-SVM). It also improves over exemplar-SVM by proposing a novel normalization procedure instead of calibrating the classifier output. <br />In my opinion, one of the strongest contribution is the normalization aspect, freeing the user form a tedious calibration procedure. What I am missing from this paper is a comparison, both experimental and from a theoretical standpoint, from the proposed normalization and the calibration. In my understanding, calibration produces a scaling and a shift of the hyperplanes, while the proposed normalization only affect the scaling. From a theoretical standpoint, the interpretation of the weights as a feature descriptor is not novel. The weight vector has already been used to perform feature selection. From a computational point of view, a linear SVM classifier is nothing more than a dot product plus a bias term, followed by a sigmoid or sign function. The proposed descriptor acts as SVM classifier with no bias term. <br /><br />The results are significant with respect to the Fisher vector and BOW approaches. However, I am not convinced about the improvements with respect to a calibration procedure. Calibration is tedious, no doubt, but it would be interesting to know what is the benefit of it. In a real application, what is important is the query time and not the learning one, especially considering the trade-off between learning time and performance. It would have been interesting to comment on the result table, specifically for the recall@20, where the increase of descriptor size reduces the performance for the proposed method.
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#284775;background-color:White;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Please summarize your review in 1-2 sentences</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            The paper presents a combination of Fisher vector and exemplar-SVM for place recognition, followed by a novel normalization of the SVM weights. The presented results are very good but I am not sure about its performance when compared to calibration techniques used already for exemplar-SVM approaches.
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Quality Score - Does the paper deserves to be published?</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            5: Marginally below the acceptance threshold
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#284775;background-color:White;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Impact Score - Independently of the Quality Score above, this is your opportunity to identify papers that are very different, original, or otherwise potentially impactful for the NIPS community.</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            1: This work is incremental and unlikely to have much impact even though it may be technically correct and well executed.
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Confidence</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            4: Reviewer is confident but not absolutely certain
                        </td>
			</tr>
		</tbody></table>
	</div>
            
        
            <hr />
            <table>
                <tbody><tr>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl02_Label2" style="font-size:Small;font-weight:bold;">Masked Reviewer ID:</span>
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl02_Label1" style="font-size:Small;">Assigned_Reviewer_38</span>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>
                        <span id="ctl00_cph_gvReviews_ctl02_Label3" style="font-size:Small;font-weight:bold;">Review:</span>
                    </td>
                    <td>
                    </td>
                </tr>
            </tbody></table>
            <div>
		<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" rules="all" border="1" style="color:#333333;border-width:1px;border-style:None;font-family:Verdana;font-size:Small;border-collapse:collapse;">
			<tbody><tr style="color:White;background-color:#5D7B9D;font-weight:bold;">
				<th scope="col">Question</th><th scope="col">&nbsp;</th>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Comments to author(s).  First provide a summary of the paper, and then address the following criteria:  Quality, clarity, originality and significance.   (For detailed reviewing guidelines, see http://nips.cc/PaperInformation/ReviewerInstructions)</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            This paper proposes introducing e-SVM and applyin it to compressed Fisher Vector for place recognition task. In the proposed method, the L2-normalized weight vectors obtained by an examplar SVM is regarded as a new image representation. Because the dimension of a normal FV is too large to store a large number of images, a compressed FV by PCA is used as a base representation to which e-SVM is applied. In the experiments, 32,768-dim FVs with 256-GMM are compressed into 128, 512, or 2014 by PCA, and then L2-normalied e-SVM weights are obtained for a new compact represenation for database images.<br /><br />Cons.)<br />1) The detail analysis on e-SVM with L2-normalied vectors is presented, and shows<br />FV can be replaced with a normalied weight vector estimated by e-SVM, which brings better representation to discriminate a positive sample from negative samples.<br /><br />2) Calibration is not needed for the similarity obtained by dot-product of the normalized weight vectors and the compressed fisher vector of a given query image. I think this is the most important finding in this paper.<br /><br />3) In the experiments, they applied the proposed e-SVM-based features to the Pittsburge 25k dataset and showed the effectiveness of the proposed method compared to [12] and [17].<br /><br />Pros.)<br />1) The reason why the proposed method is limited to only place recognition task is unclear. I expect the proposed method can be applied to generic image retrieval tasks as well, since only the point to specialize the experiments to place recognition is how to select negative samples. The proposed method is applicable for the INRIA holiday dataset and Flickr60k as well.<br /><br />2) The experiments is not comprehensive. If the main contribution of this paper is<br />a new representation which is normalized weight vectors of e-SVM, the proposed method is expected to be able to applied to other representation than PCA-compressed FV such as BOW (which is used in [12]) and FV compressed by other methods shown in [24].<br />For fair comparison, the author should add the result of BOW with e-SVM. In addition, the results with uncompressed FV should be added as the uppper bound of FV-derived methods for reference.<br /><br />3) As an alternative of e-SVM, e-LDA is proposed in [12], which also needs no calibration. No comparison is shown to [12].<br /><br />Comments)<br />1) The condition of the experiment on BOW is not written. How many visual words? Is it the same as [12]? It should be added.<br />
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#284775;background-color:White;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Please summarize your review in 1-2 sentences</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            It is interesting to avoid the needs for calibration typically needed for e-SVM based methods based on detailed analysis on e-SVM, but the experiments are not comprehensive and convincing. <br />
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Quality Score - Does the paper deserves to be published?</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            5: Marginally below the acceptance threshold
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#284775;background-color:White;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Impact Score - Independently of the Quality Score above, this is your opportunity to identify papers that are very different, original, or otherwise potentially impactful for the NIPS community.</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            1: This work is incremental and unlikely to have much impact even though it may be technically correct and well executed.
                        </td>
			</tr><tr style="color:#333333;background-color:#F7F6F3;">
				<td style="width:20%;">Confidence</td><td style="width:80%;">
                            4: Reviewer is confident but not absolutely certain
                        </td>
			</tr>
